title: For Sale/Trade:  Pelikan M400 Fountain Pen
postcontent:
Pelikan M400 Fountain Pen

A true classic

In the year 1929 Pelikan was the first company in the world to introduce the differentiated piston mechanism. This technique causes the spindle inside the fountain pen to turn quicker than the end piece of the barrel, with the help of two different threads. To this date, this fountain pen exists in many different variations, and though it has been developed in design and technical details over time, the basic mechanism remains the same.

In 1950, the model 400 was launched. With its green-striped sleeve, it has become a world-wide symbol for the brand of Pelikan. In the eighties, the series was baptized Souverän, though popular lore has taken to calling it by its nickname Stresemann, because the state secretary of the “Weimarer Republik” was famous for his striped suits... . With the models in "Black-Green" and "Black-Blue" already enjoying great popularity, the color variation "Black-Red" was added in 2001. The striped pattern of its sleeve presents itself in strong contrasted colors.

The production of the sleeve is work-intensive. Adhering to a special Pelikan recipe, the raw material cotton is processed through many different steps until it is shaped into a striped sheet. It is then formed into the right shape, cut and sanded with a diamond. Next, the characteristic double clips at the back of the barrel and on the cap are integrated into the material. This is done with the highest precision in order to obtain a virtually seamless transition between the materials. The writing instrument is then polished to a high sheen before the slightly springy clip with its famous, stylized Pelikan is mounted.

If you love classics, you own a Souverän writing instrument.

**This pen has been inked 1 time and cleaned per the instructions after use**

So, you see a Tromix Saiga-12 for sale and the buyer is asking a premium price. How do you know if it's a real Tromix gun, or simply a fake, cobbled up on someone's kitchen table? Here's a few tips to help you identify a fake from the real thing.

How to identify a real Tromix Saiga-12.

1. Your gun must have a Tromix HK style trigger guard Tig welded in place.

2. The pistol grip does not use a square hole cut in the receiver to hang it in the conventional AK style. There is a threaded rod welded to the receiver to hang the grip. There were a handful of guns, maybe 5 or so, with the square hole, but then the square nut would have been welded in place (externally) in order to make grip installation easier.

3. No Tromix guns were ever produced with an external safety stop like the factory unit. Very early guns, just had a dimple detent. Later guns had a welded in nipple on the side of the receiver to stop the safety selector.

4. All guns have a welded in back plate which has threaded inserts to bolt stock in place. No guns were made using the ACE adapter block to affix the stock. 

5. If the gun is equipped with HK sights, you can remove the rear sight and look at the welds inside. The rear mount is affixed via Tig welding front and back on the inside. If it looks like a Mig weld or the welds are in a different location, it is not a Tromix installed sight base and most likely not a Tromix gun.

6. All Tromix guns had the four extra original trigger axis pin holes welded up and blended out, as well as the rivet holes for the original trigger guard/plate. No guns were ever shipped with plastic plugs or screws in those holes.

title: For Sale:  Blade-Tech Concealex 1911
postcontent: Blade-Tech 1911 government right handed holster. This is a belt holster color stealth black. Purchased in 2001 never used, still in original packaging. Concealex is much easier to mold then the new Kydex. Blade-Tech's latest innovation is Concealex, a camouflaged form of Kydex that incorporates the camo pattern right into the plastic itself. This remarkable material is resistant to most chemicals, oils and solvents, and is absolutely waterproof. It has a permanent memory with excellent retention qualities, facilitating extremely smooth operation. The unique camouflage patterns are integrated into the Concealex and have a matte finish for tactical field applications. They blend very well with their respective BDU patterns or solids. One of our favorite Blade-Tech designs is the straight-drop holster for a 1911. This holster is approved for competition, but it is secure enough for daily carry. The front is cut down to the middle of the pistol's ejection port, a "speed cut" as Blade-Tech describes the design, but it is a far cry from the radically low-cut "competition rigs" used in IPSC.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1974 Yamaha DT250MX Vintage Motocross Racer
postcontent:
I am selling my AHRMA legal Yamaha. I built this bike for racing, but by the time I finished it, I had other projects and so it was never raced. However, I did ride it a few times and it is very fast.

The entire bike was rebuilt, new piston, rings, transmission (includes an extra transmission too), cables, levers, seat. After it was mechanically sound, I stripped it down to the frame. I removed all of the wiring to make it a dirt only machine. I removed the oiling system, and blocked off the pump to make it a pre-mix only bike. I replaced the enduro head with an MX250 head for higher compression, and dual spark plugs. The original 28mm carb was replaced by a 32mm flatside carb which improved performance A LOT. All of the suspension is from an MX250, and it has a rare fork brace. The head was redone, and it has boost ports for increased power. Even with all of that, there are some other performance mods that would make this even faster (although it would be competitive as is).

This is a really neat bike, with all of the performance of a motocross bike. The AHRMA rule book does allow this bike to run in the pre-75 classes because it is of "similar construction" to the pre-75 bikes (twin shocks). Race it, ride it on trails, etc. I will include lots of original parts, an MX250 tank, and some other new parts like sprockets, exhaust, etc.

I am looking to sell it, but I would be happy to consider trades or partial trades. Especially for a modern enduro dual sport, KLR 650, etc. I am also interested in older BMWs, airheads, 2 stroke street bikes, or GUNS. If you have an AR-15, and want to go fast instead of waste your money at the range, please contact me!..... email me or text 5FOUR1-NINE77-FIVE347
